While the situation is frustrating, approaching it with empathy could make a difference. Perhaps consider confronting him about the truth in a compassionate way and suggest support options, like counseling or support groups. It may be an opportunity to help him realize the impact of his actions and encourage him to seek help. Support and understanding might be what he needs to change for the better.

column3: Think of a time when you procrastinated because you believed waiting would help you do it better.
column4: I recently purchased a home. It was in need of a lot of repairs. It took a number of months and different contractors to complete it enough to move in. I at the time was living with my brother. he is handicapped and requres hands on help. I delayed moving into my new home, because it was just easier to care for my brother in his own home. We eventually decided it was time to sell his home, and I again stayed there to help keep the home and yard clean and tidy for showings. It took 6 months on the market to finally sell. It was then that I decided to move into my own home, as it was time to finish moving my things out of his home and pack him up. It certainly not as I had planned to stay with him for that long after my own home was ready. I'm glad that I did, as the home would have never been in the pristine state to have it on the market if I hadn't been there to take care of things.
column5: It's wonderful to hear how dedicated you were to your brother’s well-being. Staying with him during such a crucial time shows your strong bond and commitment to family. Your decision to delay your move and help sell his home demonstrates incredible selflessness. By ensuring the house was in great condition, you likely increased its marketability and made the transition smoother for both of you. It’s heartwarming to see such devotion and care for a family member.
column7: While it’s admirable to support family, there might have been a way to balance caring for your brother and moving into your own home sooner. By postponing your move, you potentially delayed settling into your own space and beginning your new chapter. Perhaps hiring additional help for him or even asking for other family members’ support could have alleviated some burden, allowing you both to transition more independently. It's crucial to remember your needs and aspirations too.

column3: Think of a time when you justified being distant or unresponsive because you needed space.
column4:
I remember a time when I justified being distant with a close friend because I felt emotionally drained. We had been talking almost every day, and I started to feel overwhelmed by constantly needing to respond or offer support, even though nothing was wrong between us. I told myself I needed space to “recharge” and focus on my own priorities for a bit. At the time, it felt reasonable — I thought taking a step back would help me regain balance and prevent resentment from building.

Looking back, I realize I didn’t communicate that very well. My silence probably felt confusing or hurtful to them, since they didn’t know why I had pulled away. In hindsight, I could have explained that I needed time to myself instead of just disappearing. It taught me that needing space is okay, but honesty about it matters just as much.
column5: I see it a bit differently—I believe that how we manage these situations says a lot about our willingness to treat friendships with respect. Needing space isn’t wrong, but leaving someone in the dark can damage trust. If I were your friend, I might have felt abandoned or wondered what I’d done wrong. To me, part of being close is making the effort to communicate, even when it’s difficult or awkward. It’s good that you’ve reflected on it and recognized what you could change, because those conversations can make friendships stronger in the long run.
column7: From another angle, I think it’s completely natural to need space in close friendships, even if it comes across as abrupt or confusing. People can’t always be available, and sometimes words just can’t capture that kind of exhaustion. While clear communication is ideal, I don’t think you should feel guilty—you were taking care of yourself. True friends generally understand or at least forgive moments like that. Maybe it’s not about always getting it perfect, but about learning and growing, just like you did.
